<?xml version='1.0' encoding='UTF-8'?>
<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1939-12-27T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1939-12-27T00:00:00-05:00" n="595" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d595">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">622.006/94</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">The Chargé in Ecuador</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Gade</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the
                                    <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                            </hi>
                        </head>
                        <opener>
                            <seg rendition="#left">No. 795</seg>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Quito</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1939-12-27">December 27,
                                1939</date>.<lb/>[Received January 2, 1940.]</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: With reference to the Legation’s telegram
                            No. 100 of December 13, 1939,<note n="53" xml:id="d595fn53">Not
                                printed.</note> reporting that the Import Control System will be
                            abolished on January 1, 1940, I now have the honor to transmit herewith
                            the text of Executive Decree No. 14 of December 23, 1939 (as published
                            in <hi rend="italic">El Comercio</hi> on the following day), which
                            abolishes the System.</p>
                        <pb facs="0641" n="633" xml:id="pg_633"/>
                        <p>An English translation of the Decree<note n="54" xml:id="d595fn54">Not
                                printed.</note> is also enclosed for the Department’s
                            information.</p>
                        <p>Respectfully yours,</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Gerhard Gade</hi>
                            </signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                </body></text></TEI>